The Nigerian health sector is evidently confronted with a series of challenges, which includes a declining workforce as the sector’s human resource profile falls short of the World Health Organisation (WHO)’s recommendation. The Federal Ministry of Health in collaboration with the WHO recently launched the Nigeria Health Workforce Profile 2018, an update of the 2012 profile, and handed over of the Nigeria Health Workforce Registry. The profile revealed that Nigeria has a ratio of one doctor to 2,753 members of the population whereas WHO recommends one doctor to 600 members of the population. It also shows that the number of medical doctors registered with the Medical and Dental Council of Nigeria (MDCN) is 74,543 which equates to 36.3 medical doctors per 100,000 population; a doctor to population ratio of 1: 2753. The data shows a variation in the distribution of medical doctors by state of practice from the reported 2012 density, as the Federal Capital Territory (FCT), in 2012, had the highest density of 82 medical doctors per 100,000 population, whereas that of Katsina reduced from 2.5 per 100,000 population in 2012 to  2.0 per 100,000 population, and Zamfara increased marginally from 2.5 per 100,000 population to 2.7 per 100,000 population.  Nurses and Midwives: According to the new profile, there are 180,709 registered nurses. This equates to 88.1 nurses per 100,000 members of the population (nurse to population ratio of 1: 1,135). Registered midwives are 120,870 which equates to 58.9 midwives per 100,000 members of the population (midwife to population ratio of 1:1,697). The data shows a reduction in the density of midwives by 1.7 per cent from the 2012 density of 59.9 per 100,000 population to 58.9 per 100,000 population in 2018.  Pharmacists: 24,668 pharmacists were registered with the Pharmacists Council of Nigeria (PCN) in 2018, and this equates to 12 pharmacists per 100,000 members of the population (pharmacist to population ratio of 1:8,317). Also, the profile captured 5,793 registered pharmacy technicians, which is 2.8 pharmacy technicians per 100,000 population (pharmacy technician to population ratio of 1:35,417). Presenting the data, the head, Human Resources for Health (HRH), Federal Ministry of Health, Shakusi Kadiri, said that although there was a decline in the numbers recorded in 2007, there is a progressive increase in the numbers of medical doctors applying for letters of good standing or verification (a proxy for migration)  from 656 in  2014 to 1551 in 2018. Speaking at the event, the Minister of Health, Dr Osagie Ehanire, said that the health sector was faced with a series of challenges which he said has affected the delivery of quality health care services to the rising population. These challenges, according to him, include inadequate investments in human resources in the health sector to provide the required information as and at when it is due, and inadequate capacity of health institutions to meet the demand of health workers with supply though the country has one of the largest stock of human resources for health in Africa, comparable only to Egypt and South Africa. “Nigeria has over the years increased its production, but has consistently lost health workers due to migration and brain drain because of inadequate motivation, remuneration, and incentives,” Ehanire said. Continuing, he said, “Health workers within the country’s health system have remained the weakest link, resulting in the loss of critical investments. While Nigeria is currently developing a functional Health Workforce Registry after the publication of the National Health Workforce Profile 2008 and 2012, the current National Strategic Health Development Plan (NSHDP II) was also challenged with the availability of the right, accurate national HRH evidence to inform planning in critical intervention areas. “This huge gap has implication for accuracy of strategies, efficiency in deploying resources requirement, and effectiveness of monitoring and evaluation.” According to him, the registry is a single and authoritative source of authenticated and validated health workforce information in the country, which provides up-to-date information on all health workers under the employment of national and sub-national entities in both public and private sectors of the national health system. Also speaking at the event, the immediate past WHO Officer in Charge, Nigeria, Dr. Clement Peters, said the Nigeria Health Workforce Registry serves as a database for accurate and timely evidence-based health workforce information and it links health workers to administrative units and health facilities. According to him, “The registry demonstrates Nigeria’s significant progress in achieving the Global Strategy for Human Resources for Health: the Workforce 2030 milestone of every country having a registry to track health workforce dynamics and sharing HRH data annually through the National Health Workforce accounts. “It also sets the foundation for achieving the goal of the Strategic Pillar 3 and Priority Area 9 of the Second National Strategic Health Development Plan 2018 – 2022 of having in place the right number and skill mix of competent, motivated, productive, and equitably distributed health workforce for optimal and quality health care service provision.” Peters informed that the WHO, with funding from the Government of Canada developed the prototype of the Registry, using the iHRIS Manage framework which is being used in several countries globally. He said, “The WHO also supported the roll out of the registry in Bauchi and Cross River States with funding from the Government of Canada through the Global Affairs Canada; Anambra and Sokoto States with funding from the European Union; Borno, Adamawa, Abia, Osun, Niger, and Edo with funding from the Government of Japan and the WHO. We are also in the process of concluding the registry for Yobe State.”